{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:17:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:17:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11427"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11427"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.29,0.27,0.14,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109168"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4061"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91523"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4639"},{"type":"tags","id":"4653"},{"type":"tags","id":"4705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4820"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17216"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36522"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40057"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45015"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109168"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of a painless ulcer on her vulva. She has not had any new rashes, fever or malaise. On further questioning, she has had sexual intercourse with three male partners within the past month. She mentioned that she often forgot to use condoms. She is G1P0, 16 weeks pregnant and has not had prior antenatal care. Her medical history is unremarkable except for an allergic reaction two years ago to amoxicillin which caused a rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is no obvious rash on her palms, face or feet. The ulcer is on the left labia majora, has raised edges and has a base that is firm, red and clean. There are a few small enlarged lymph nodes in the inguinal region that are non-tender. A swab of the ulcer confirms your most likely diagnosis and all other testing is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IM benzathine benzylpenicillin weekly for three weeks","Referral for penicillin desensitisation","Single dose of IM ceftriaxone and oral azithromycin","Oral doxycycline for 14 days","Single dose of IM benzathine benzylpenicillin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has primary syphilis, characterised by a painless ulcer (chancre) and regional lymphadenopathy. The history of multiple sexual partners and inconsistent condom use increases her risk for sexually transmitted infections. The diagnosis is confirmed by the swab of the ulcer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for penicillin desensitisation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient. Intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin remains the most recommended treatment for syphilis at all stages, and the best alternative, doxycycline, is not appropriate in pregnancy. Given the patient\u0027s history of allergic reaction to amoxicillin, she should have penicillin after undergoing desensitisation. According to the Australian STI guidelines, only penicillin has been shown to be effective in pregnancy, so those allergic should be desensitised and thereafter treated with penicillin. Pregnant people should be managed urgently with specialist advice, and fetal monitoring may be advised if more than 20 weeks of pregnancy. Partner testing and presumptive treatment are also recommended, and repeat testing during pregnancy is needed to confirm response and detect re-infection. Birth and post-natal testing of the mother and clinical review of the baby at delivery are also advised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline for 14 days\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used as an alternative treatment for syphilis in penicillin-allergic patients. However, it is not the preferred option when penicillin desensitisation is possible, as penicillin remains the gold standard treatment. Additionally, it is not safe in pregnancy and can affect the development of teeth and bones in the fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose of IM benzathine benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment for primary syphilis, but it cannot be given without prior desensitisation in this patient due to her history of penicillin allergy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIM benzathine benzylpenicillin weekly for three weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is the standard treatment for late syphilis or syphilis of unknown duration. This is not appropriate as the clinical history in this case is very clear of primary syphilis, and again, it cannot be administered due to her history of severe penicillin allergy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose of IM ceftriaxone and oral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for syphilis treatment. While this combination is used for gonorrhoea, it is not effective against syphilis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPenicillin desensitisation is a process where gradually increasing doses of penicillin are administered over several hours, allowing the patient to tolerate the full therapeutic dose. This procedure is typically performed in a hospital setting under close medical supervision. It can usually be completed in a single day, making it feasible even for patients from remote locations. After successful desensitisation, the patient can receive the appropriate penicillin treatment for syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Penicillin is the best recommended treatment for syphilis, and desensitisation should be considered over any alternatives.","Doxycycline is not an appropriate treatment in pregnancy.","The process of penicillin desensitisation can typically be completed in a single day at a tertiary hospital."],"references":["ASHM Organisation. Syphilis - Australian STI Management Guidelines [Internet]. Australian STI management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care:2019 [cited 7 December 2021]. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/syphilis/","WHO Guidelines for the Treatment of Treponema pallidum (Syphilis). Geneva: World Health Organization; 2016. 4, RECOMMENDATIONS FOR TREATMENT OF SYPHILIS. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK384905/","Chastain DB, Hutzley VJ, Parekh J, Alegro JVG. Antimicrobial Desensitization: A Review of Published Protocols. Pharmacy (Basel). 2019 Aug 9;7(3):112. doi: 10.3390/pharmacy7030112. PMID: 31405062; PMCID: PMC6789802. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6789802/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91523"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11427"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91523"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-19T09:58:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-19T09:58:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4061"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109168"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCo